ntsync 1013: dedicated kmem_cache for ntsync_event_pi / ntsync_channel_entry / ntsync_pi_owner

Replace generic kzalloc / kfree with per-struct dedicated kmem_cache for
the three structs allocated on the gamma audio dispatcher hot path:

  - ntsync_event_pi      ~96B  (allocated up to 2x per SEND_PI + 1x per
                                RECV/RECV2/TRY_RECV2 + 1x per EVENT_SET_PI;
                                was kmalloc-128 generic)
  - ntsync_channel_entry ~128-256B (1x per SEND_PI; was kmalloc-256)
  - ntsync_pi_owner      (allocated by ntsync_pi_work_prealloc on every
                          mutex-path wait/wake; was kmalloc-N generic)

Dedicated caches give us tighter cache-line packing (SLAB_HWCACHE_ALIGN),
better per-cpu freelist locality (the gamma dispatcher cycles through
the same cache constantly rather than sharing kmalloc-128 with system-
wide xattr / dentry / fd / network buffer callers), and visibility in
/proc/slabinfo for future tuning.

GFP_KERNEL semantics preserved — these allocations stay outside the
raw_spin obj_lock per the existing PREEMPT_RT discipline (cf. the
ntsync_pi_work_prealloc + obj_lock pattern that was already established
for kfree-under-raw-spinlock avoidance).

NULL-safety asymmetry vs kfree
==============================

kmem_cache_free(s, x) is NOT NULL-safe.  Per mm/slub.c:6900:

  void kmem_cache_free(struct kmem_cache *s, void *x)
  {
      s = cache_from_obj(s, x);  // derefs x via virt_to_cache(x) when
                                 // SLAB_FREELIST_HARDENED is enabled
      if (!s) return;
      ...
  }

  static inline struct kmem_cache *cache_from_obj(struct kmem_cache *s,
                                                  void *x)
  {
      if (!IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_SLAB_FREELIST_HARDENED) &&
          !kmem_cache_debug_flags(s, SLAB_CONSISTENCY_CHECKS))
          return s;
      cachep = virt_to_cache(x);  // ← faults on NULL: virt_to_folio(NULL)
                                  //   = vmemmap[0] = 0xffffebde00000000
                                  //   (x86_64) → reads slab->slab_cache
                                  //   at offset 8 → faults at
                                  //   0xffffebde00000008
      ...
  }

Contrast: kfree(x) has an explicit `if (unlikely(ZERO_OR_NULL_PTR(x)))
return;` early-out.

Every conversion site in this patch where the freed pointer can legally
be NULL is therefore explicitly guarded by `if (ptr)`.  The audit covers:

  - Pointer-from-list-iteration sites (loop variables, non-NULL by
    construction): unguarded, OK.
  - Pointer-from-allocation sites (k*alloc + NULL-check earlier in the
    function, then later free on error path): unguarded, OK.
  - Pointer-from-struct-field sites (where the field is NULL whenever
    no pending state is staged): EXPLICITLY GUARDED.
  - Refcount-protected free sites (only freed when refcount hits 0,
    and refcount=1 was set at allocation): unguarded, OK.

The struct-field NULL case bit us on first deployment (post1014, srcversion
6586C76CC11DB19652A19A5, crashed at 22:12:34 boot -1 2026-05-04 with
exactly the kmem_cache_free+0x5c vmemmap[0]+8 fault described above).
The fix landed before this patch was finalized — site is the
`obj->u.event.pending_pi.new_ep` free in ntsync_free_obj, which is NULL
in the common case where an event dies without an unconsumed SET_PI
staging.

Validation
==========

post1014a srcversion F1A9EA24E257A35BB21341D, debug kernel
6.19.11-rt1-1-nspa-debug (KASAN+KCSAN+lockdep+SLAB_FREELIST_HARDENED):

  test-mixed-load-stress 300s   5.28M chan SEND/REPLY   0 errors  KASAN clean
  test-channel-stress 60s 4x4   1.40M SEND/REPLY        0 errors  KASAN clean
  test-channel-try-recv2 30s 4  62k SEND, 2.68M attempts 0 errors KASAN clean

~14M total ntsync ops on post1014a, zero kernel splats — including the
exact code path (ntsync_free_obj of a pending_pi-clean event) that fired
the original crash.

